% purāṇāni? or aśī for aśīti 80?
<TEXT> purāṇāśīsahasrāṇi śatāni dvijasattama|</TEXT>
        <!-- <TR>O truest of the twice-born, the Purāṇa[s of] 8,000,000 [verses]</TR> -->
        <APP>\vb <LEM>°sattama</LEM> \msCa\msCb\msNa\msNc\msM\Ed; ××maḥ  \msCc</APP>
        <NOTE>ŁPāda$ a should probably be analysed and interpreted as 
                        Łpurāṇam (purāṇānām aśītisahasrāṇi śatāni ślokāni) brahmaṇā kathitam$.
                        Alternatively, Łpāda$ a may have originally read Łpurāṇāni sahasrāṇi$,
                        and then the inital number of verses transmitted by Brahmā is
                        a hundred thousand. That the number refers to the number of Łśloka$s
                        transmitted, and not, e.g., the number of lines, is confirmed in 1.66d:
                        Łviṃśatślokasahasrikam$.

              On the idea that initially there was only one Purāṇa, see, e.g.,
              <citep>RocherPuranas1986</citep><pnum>41ff</pnum>.

              <sep/>
              In Łpāda$ d, either understand Łmātariśvā$ (nom.) as Łmātariśvānaṃ$ (acc.) or emend
              Łkathitaṃ$ to Łkathitaḥ$ in the sense `Mātariśvan was taught,' echoing 1.39cd:
              Łbrahmaṇā yat purākhyāto mātariśvā yathā tathā$.

                <sep/>
                Compare this list to a list of twenty-eight Łvedavyāsa$s, from
                Brahmā to Vyāsa Dvaipāyana, in \VISNUP\ 3.3.10--19,
                taught by Parāśara, the twenty-sixth Łvyāsa$
                of this list and our text (in the numbering that I add here I follow
                the translation in <citep>Visnupurana_tr</citep><pnum>178--179</pnum>):
                <sep/>
                Łvedavyāsā vyatītā ye aṣṭāviṃśati sattama~|
                caturdhā yaiḥ kṛto vedo dvāpareṣu punaḥ punaḥ~||
                dvāpare prathame vyastāḥ svayaṃ vedāḥ $[1]Ł svayaṃbhuvā~|<br/>
                dvitīye dvāpare caiva vedavyāsaḥ $[2]Ł prajāpati~||<br/>
                tṛtīye $[3]Ł cośanā vyāsaś caturthe ca $[4]Ł bṛhaspatiḥ~| <br/>
                $[5]Ł savitā pañcame vyāsaḥ $[6]Ł mṛtyuḥ ṣaṣṭhe smṛtaḥ prabhuḥ~|| <br/>
                saptame ca $[7]Ł tathaivendro $[8]Ł vasiṣṭhaś cāṣṭame smṛtaḥ~| <br/>
                $[9]Ł sārasvataś ca navame $[10]Ł tridhāmā daśame smṛtaḥ~|| <br/>
                ekādaśe tu $[11]Ł trivṛṣā $[12]Ł bhāradvājas tataḥ param~| <br/>
                trayodaśe $[13]Ł cāntarikṣo $[14]Ł varṇī cāpi caturdaśe~|| <br/>
                $[15]Ł trayyāruṇaḥ pañcadaśe ṣoḍaśe tu $[16]Ł dhanaṃjayaḥ~| <br/>
                $[17]Ł kratuṃjayaḥ saptadaśe $[18]Ł ṛṇajyo 'ṣṭādaśe smṛtaḥ~|| <br/>
                tato vyāso $[19]Ł bharadvājo bharadvājāt tu $[20]Ł gautamaḥ~| <br/>
                gautamād uttamo vyāso $[21]Ł haryātmā yo 'bhidhīyate~|| <br/>
                atha haryātmano $[22]Ł venaḥ smṛto vājaśravās tu yaḥ~| <br/>
                somaḥ śuṣmāyaṇas tasmāt $[23]Ł tṛṇabindur iti smṛtaḥ~|| <br/>
                $[24]Ł ṛkṣo 'bhūd bhārgavas tasmād vālmīkir yo 'bhidhīyate~| <br/>
                tasmād asmatpitā $[25]Ł śaktir vyāsas tasmād $[26]Ł ahaṃ mune~|| <br/>
                $[27]Ł jātukarṇo 'bhavan mattaḥ kṛṣṇadvaipāyanas $[28]Ł tataḥ~| <br/>
                aṣṭaviṃśatir ity ete vedavyāsāḥ purātanāḥ~||  <br/>$

                <sep/>
                Another relevant passage is \BrahmandaPur\ 3.4.58cd--67 (\similar\ \VayuP\ 2.41.58--67).
                Note how Tṛṇabindu is, perhaps by mistake, different from Somaśuṣma/Śuṣmāyaṇa here,
                but, more importantly, note Amitabuddhi of \VSS\ 1.76 appear at the end of this list:
                <sep/>
                [1] Łbrahmā dadau śāstram idaṃ purāṇaṃ $[2]Ł mātariśvane~|| <br/>
                tasmāc $[3]Ł cośanasā prāptaṃ tasmāc cāpi $[4]Ł bṛhaspatiḥ~|   <br/>
                bṛhaspatis tu provāca $[5]Ł savitre tadanantaram~||   <br/>
                savitā  $[6]Ł mṛtyave prāha mṛtyuś $[7]Ł cendrāya vai punaḥ~| <br/>
                indraś cāpi $[8]Ł vasiṣṭāya so 'pi $[9]Ł sārasvatāya ca~|| <br/>
                sārasvatas $[10]Ł tridhāmne 'tha tridhāmā ca $[11]Ł śaradvate~| <br/>
                śaradvāṃs tu $[12]Ł triviṣṭāya so $[13]Ł 'ntarikṣāya dattavān~|| <br/>
                $[14]Ł carṣiṇe cāntarikṣo vai so 'pi $[15]Ł trayyāruṇāya ca~| <br/>
                trayyāruṇād $[16]Ł dhanañjayaḥ sa vai prādāt $[17]Ł kṛtañjaye~|| <br/>
                kṛtañjayāt $[18]Ł tṛṇañjayo $[19]Ł bharadvājāya so 'py atha~|   <br/>
                $[20]Ł gautamāya bharadvājaḥ so 'pi $[21]Ł niryyantare punaḥ~|| <br/>
                niryyantaras tu provāca tathā $[22]Ł vājaśravāya vai~|   <br/>
                sa dadau $[23]Ł somaśuṣmāya sa cādāt $[24]Ł tṛṇabindave~|| <br/>
                tṛṇabindus tu $[25]Ł dakṣāya dakṣaḥ provāca $[26]Ł śaktaye~| <br/>
                śakteḥ $[27]Ł parāśaraś cāpi garbhasthaḥ śrutavān idam~|| <br/>
                parāśarāj $[28]Ł jātukarṇyas tasmād $[29]Ł dvaipāyanaḥ prabhuḥ~|   <br/>
                dvaipāyanāt punaś cāpi $[30]Ł mayā prāptaṃ dvijottama~|| <br/>
                mayā caitat punaḥ proktaṃ $[31]Ł putrāyāmitabuddhaye~|   <br/>
                ity eva vākyaṃ brahmādiguruṇāṃ samudāhṛtam~||  $ <br/>

                <sep/>
                The list of Łvedavyāsa$s in \LinPu\ 1.7.15--18 includes these twenty-five names:
                Kratu, Satya, Bhārgava, Aṅgiras, Savitṛ,
                Mṛtyu, Śatakratu, Vasiṣṭha, Sārasvata, Tridhāman,
                Trivṛta, Śatatejas, Tarakṣu, Āruṇi, Kṛtaṃjaya,
                Ṛtaṃjayo, Bharadvāja, Gautama, Vācaśravas, Tṛṇabindu,
                Rūkṣa, Śakti, Jātūkarṇya, Kṛṣṇa Dvaipāyano.</NOTE>


