              more than possible within the style of this text.

              I have not been able find any attestation of Łvyoman$ meaning the five elements. Perhaps it is meant
              to mean Łvyomādi$ (`the atmosphere/sky and the other four elements'). 
        
                For Śiva of eight forms, see, e.g., ŁŚakuntalā$ 1.1:
        <sep/>
                        Łyā sṛṣṭiḥ sraṣṭur ādyā [1] vahati vidhihutaṃ yā havir [2] yā ca hotrī [3]<br/>
                        ye dve kālaṃ vidhattaḥ [4,5] śruti-viṣaya-guṇā yā [6] sthitā vyāpya viśvam |<br/>
                        yām āhuḥ sarva-bīja-prakṛtir [7] iti yayā prāṇinaḥ prāṇavantaḥ [8]<br/>
                        pratyakṣābhiḥ prapannas tanubhir avatu vas tābhir aṣṭābhir īśaḥ ||$.<br/>
                 The eight Łmūrti$s, or rather, Łtanu$s, here are: 
                        [1] Łjala$ [2] Łagni$ [3] Łyajamāna$ [4,5] Łsūrya$ + Łcandra$ [6] Łākāśa$ [7] Łbhūmi$ [8] Łvāyu$.

